\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.5 Formal Sanctions Process and CJIS Notification
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
The Department shall employ a formal sanctions process for individuals who fail to comply with the policies and procedures established in the ECIO Policy Manual.
 This process is consistent with applicable County HR policies,
 labor agreements,
 and NIST SP 800-53 Rev.
 5:
 PS-8 (Personnel Sanctions).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Initiation
\series default
:
 The IT Director initiates the formal sanctions process by documenting the non-compliance,
 the IT-administrative actions taken,
 and a recommendation for formal discipline.
 The IT Director shall refer the documented matter to HR and/or the County Manager for processing through the applicable personnel framework.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Process Ownership
\series default
:
 The formal sanctions process is governed by the applicable labor agreement,
 County Personnel Policies,
 or employment contract —
 not by this policy.
 This policy defines the trigger conditions,
 the documentation the IT Director provides,
 and the CJIS notification obligation.
 It does not define the investigation,
 notice,
 response,
 or appeal procedures,
 which are established in the applicable personnel framework.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
CJIS Notification Requirement
\series default
:
 In accordance with CJIS Security Policy v6.0:
 Section PS-8 (Personnel Sanctions) and NIST SP 800-53 Rev.
 5:
 PS-8,
 when a formal sanctions process is initiated against any individual with access to Criminal Justice Information (CJI),
 the IT Director (as LASO) shall notify the appropriate Information Security Officer (ISO),
 HR representative,
 and System or Network Administrator within twenty-four (24) hours.
 The notification shall identify the individual sanctioned and the reason for the sanction,
 unless County legal counsel determines a different timing is legally required.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Legal Referral
\series default
:
 Where non-compliance involves suspected criminal activity —
 including but not limited to violations of NRS 205 (Computer Crimes) or unauthorized access to CJI —
 the IT Director shall refer the matter to the District Attorney's Office and,
 where applicable,
 to the appropriate law enforcement authority.
 Legal referral does not preclude concurrent IT-administrative action;
 the IT Director shall take immediate system-level protective action as warranted.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.6 Exception Management
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
All policies within the ECIO Policy Manual are subject to a uniform exception management framework.
 Exceptions to any policy requirement shall be governed by the following requirements.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Written Documentation
\series default
:
 All exceptions shall be documented in writing prior to implementation.
 The documentation shall include the specific policy requirement from which the exception is sought,
 the business justification,
 the proposed duration,
 the compensating controls (if any),
 and the residual risk accepted.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Approval Authority
\series default
:
 Exceptions shall be approved in writing by the IT Director within delegated authority under 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:1.08"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
.
 Exceptions that exceed the IT Director's delegated authority shall be approved by the County Manager.
 Oral exceptions are not valid.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Operational Tier
\series default
:
 The Assistant IT Director may approve an operational exception without IT Director pre-approval when the exception meets all of the following criteria:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
The exception duration does not exceed thirty (30) calendar days.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
The exception does not affect Criminal Justice Information handling,
 storage,
 transmission,
 or access.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
The exception does not deviate from a security baseline defined in 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:2.10"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
 (Secure Configuration Baselines and Hardening Policy).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
The exception does not deviate from a mandatory CJIS Security Policy requirement.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
The exception does not alter decision rights,
 chain of command,
 or authority structure governed by 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:1.08"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Operational Tier Controls
\series default
:
 The Assistant IT Director shall document each approved operational exception in writing and notify the IT Director within one (1) business day of approval.
 The IT Director may override any operational exception at any time.
 The Assistant IT Director shall not renew an operational exception;
 renewal requires IT Director approval.
 All other requirements in this section apply to operational exceptions without modification.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Policy-Specific Requirements
\series default
:
 Where a policy's Section 4 establishes exception requirements that are stricter than this general framework,
 the stricter requirement governs.
 Exceptions to this policy (
\series bold
Policy 
