\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.7 Legal and Regulatory Alignment
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
The ECIO Policy Manual operates within and supports compliance with applicable federal,
 state,
 and local law.
 The IT Director shall maintain awareness of legal and regulatory changes that affect the manual's obligations and shall ensure the manual remains aligned with current requirements.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Monitoring Responsibility
\series default
:
 The IT Director shall monitor changes to the Nevada Revised Statutes,
 the Nevada Administrative Code,
 the CJIS Security Policy,
 and applicable federal law and regulation that affect the manual's scope.
 The IT Director may designate qualified personnel to assist with monitoring but retains accountability for the alignment determination.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Event-Driven Review
\series default
:
 When a legal or regulatory change is identified that affects one or more policies in the manual,
 the IT Director shall initiate an event-driven review in accordance with 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:1.05"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
.
 The review shall assess the impact of the change,
 identify the affected policies,
 and produce the necessary updates.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Order of Precedence
\series default
:
 Where a conflict between the ECIO Policy Manual and a legal or regulatory requirement is identified,
 the legal requirement prevails.
 The order of authority established in the Compliance Alignment & Order of Precedence section of the Manual Executive Summary governs the resolution hierarchy.
 The IT Director shall update the affected policy within the next scheduled review cycle,
 or sooner if the conflict creates immediate compliance risk.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Statutory Awareness (Non-Exhaustive)
\series default
:
 The following statutes and regulations are of primary relevance to the manual's enforcement and compliance obligations.
 This list is maintained for operational awareness and does not constitute a comprehensive legal analysis.
 NRS 205 (Computer Crimes),
 NRS 239 (Public Records),
 NRS 239.125 (Local Government Records Management Program),
 NRS 242.171 (Responsibilities of Office/Director),
 NRS 244 (Counties:
 Government),
 NRS 281A (Ethics in Government),
 NRS 603A (Security of Personal Information),
 and the CJIS Security Policy as published by the FBI Criminal Justice Information Services Division.
\end_layout

